description.plain:
Porter Robinson is an American electronic music producer and singer. He is known for coining the term ‘complextro’, a portmanteau of ‘complex’ and ‘electro’ used to refer to the intricately detailed style of house music as popularised by his Spitfire EP (2011). He drastically changed his sound, moving in a more Melodic EDM direction for his debut album, Worlds in 2014.

He also frequently collaborates with other artists: his commissioned remixes span from Lady Gaga to Innerpartysystem, and he provided backing vocals for Zedd’s 2012 chart smash “Clarity”.

In 2016, He released the single “Shelter” with electronic artist Madeon. Both being very close friends for a long time, they went on a North American tour, which would expand to a European tour with stops in Japan and Australia. The Shelter Tour ended with the last stop being Coachella 2017.

In January 2020, Porter Robinson announced Nurture, his sophomore LP that further evolved his music into Indie Synthpop. The album released on April 23rd, 2021.

songs.title: Flicker

description.plain: “Flicker” is the only Japanese track on Worlds. The vocals were created from unused song titles that Porter ran through a translation tool and read out with text-to-speech. According to Porter, it wasn’t originally meant to be a Worlds song, but ended up being “One of the ones [he’s] proudest of.”

songs.full_title: Sad Machine by Porter Robinson
songs.title: Sad Machine

description.plain:
The second single from Porter Robinson’s debut album Worlds, “Sad Machine” is the first track where we get to hear Porter singing. It’s a duet with the virtual singer (Vocaloid) AVANNA and marks a new direction in Porter’s music.

According to the Commentary Album on Spotify, this was the last track he wrote for the album Worlds

songs.title: Goodbye To A World

description.plain:
“Goodbye To A World” is the final track from Porter Robinson’s debut album Worlds, released on August 12, 2014.

In a track-by-track album commentary on Spotify, Porter stated that “Goodbye to A World” was inspired by a large, violent storm outside of his house.
